Pneumococcal vaccination will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococci will overturn old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
Voices are already rising, saying compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are culminating.
The Pharmaceutical Institute already defines for vaccines the maximum prices that health insurance will pay.
The specialists also see clear in the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccinations for children in August.
Since January, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococci.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If you started vaccination last year or earlier, you will have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of the vaccine should be administered between the 3rd and 5th month of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococcal disease.
Parents paid 1,600 crowns or more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Experts estimate that each year health insurance spends 300 to 450,000 crowns on vaccine doses.
However, they save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would need.
To date, the state has spent about 500,000 crowns per year on all vaccination of children.
The refunded vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococci are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the meninges and blood poisoning.
According to hospital surveys, there are up to 28 deaths of children under the age of 10 caused by pneumococcal infections.
Aside from the Czech Republic, some 40 other countries have introduced reimbursed vaccination.
Will vaccination be compulsory?
There are opinions regarding a possible vaccination requirement in the future.
As of January, it must be settled by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD> said that compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
Its association has long promoted pneumococcal vaccination.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy to have been able to impose at least this.
I think this is a direction that we must now follow, said Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD>.
But the Ministry of Health does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination process.
We are absolutely not considering it at the moment, said its spokesperson Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>.
Optional vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Specialized Society of Pediatricians, acknowledges that a vaccination based on volunteerism has its shortcomings.
If all children were vaccinated, a reduction in vaccination renewals could be considered "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a large amount, I understand the decision making vaccination optional," Cabrnochová said.
Experts predict that as of next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will have their infants vaccinated.
Pneumococcal vaccination marks a break also because it is the first child vaccination that is funded by insurance and not the state.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance companies should release funds for prevention, thus saving on possible future medical care.
Doctors will need to buy their own products.
This, however, is related to the concerns of pediatric practitioners, which relate to the purchase of vaccines.
The original intention was to have the vaccines purchased by insurance companies, with doctors receiving them in the same way as other vaccine products provided by the state.
Some MEPs, however, feared that this would allow insurance companies to "deduct the sums of health insurance."
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurance to reimburse them.
It is estimated that pediatricians will each have to invest around 40,000 crowns per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochová.
