United Nations group has draft emission reduction plans
The UN-sponsored climate conference - characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations - came back under the spotlight on Friday, due to the release of a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations supporting most of the burden in the next 40 years.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it shed light on the way forward.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in the time-consuming negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Drafted by a UN ad hoc working group, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, both in the long run and in the long run.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed and emerging new economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature rise that officials would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN Executive Secretary-General on climate change Yvo de Boer described as “the complete picture.”
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020, by 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched the negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, U.S. Representative for Climate Negotiation, rejected any discussion requiring industrialized countries to reduce greenhouse gases, compared to voluntary efforts by major emerging economies if they were not financed by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is getting tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not insist enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after China’s deputy foreign minister, He Yafei, said the U.S. chief negotiator either lacked “common sense” or was “extremely irresponsible” for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not financially help China to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, deficiencies have emerged both within the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about rescuing individual economies than rescuing the planet, with China and the United States quarrelling over their respective obligations as poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even if vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold large emitters accountable for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change said they would continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most major participants say the negotiations will lead to a political agreement at a minimum.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission's climate unit, said that the action of the small island states has "put political pressure on the entire political process", in part by what they are now unified and that they are asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
Debates became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the pending issues before heads of government reached an agreement.
High-level officials such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister Ramesh got off their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and briefings, so they could make claims that would be considered in the following week.
The real picture of the rally -- in which 13,000 people enter and leave the Palais des Congrès every day -- of activist guitar players presenting nighttime shows mocking countries they believe are betraying each other and proposing to be written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We enter the courtyard of the greats, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
