A managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain.
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees recalls the position of companies vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of adhering employees to "values" determined from above as it used to be, to impose on consumers products thought by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences returns regularly!
Employee demobilization can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires from employees a commitment that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That’s why we call for a managerial revolution that would involve putting employees at the centre of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First because I was able to see that, faced with a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many detours, to do as a priority... what it has always done.!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from the major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leviers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr reinforces the leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, unsuited to the world today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies requires adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental observation: for employees, engagement for the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to realize part of their dreams, ambitions, projects.
Currently, only studies from the motifional analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "on the spot".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of a robust and efficient economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: 'Just War' Worth Praising Obama Right
The right-wing United States on Friday welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo the day before, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
