The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50 meters high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa findae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which was at the time part of the emerging lands of the supercontinent, the Pangea, and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa illuminates the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the relationship, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt began excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says they sometimes found a dozen bones in one day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating back to the Triassic.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
Researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a quite exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all palaeontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he specifies that it confirms certain theories concerning the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Saurians were divided into three major evolutionary groups: theropods (carnivores) that include the tyrannosaur and velociraptor that later appeared and of which descend birds, sauropods, long-necked quadrupeds, and those related to them and herbivores that include the ornithisch species and herbivores.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa was one of the first theropods.
This species presents an interesting relationship of characteristics both primitive and developed, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found evidence that the Tawa finda had small aerial sacs in its skull bones, just like the birds that are the descendants of the theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in the Tawa ella, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the huge sauropods also possessed aerial sacks and a light frame, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the Saurians appeared there.
As a result, the three great evolutionary lines have divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is, the whole of the emerged lands that formed the supercontinent Pangea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot be descended from a common ancestor who migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says that there is an even older species, the silesaurus, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a wrong view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, remains a mystery today.
During the Triassic era, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread throughout the planet, fostering the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
However, such a success is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs have survived randomly while other reptiles are reported to have disappeared.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a favorable meteorite flourishing of a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic period and that since then vegetated in the shadows: it was mammals.
