For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place of search for secret weapons, under strict supervision.
Today with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the center of Moscow, the commune has a reputation as the Soviet "Silicon Valley".
Important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics are located here.
In September 2008, representatives from Zelenograd established links with Riedberg, the Frankfurt Science Centre – with university institutes and companies at the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a "Protocol of close cooperation".
The signatories were the Deputy Mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and the Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz head of the project section for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of FIZ and SMEs, with a strong focus on scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will allow FIZ companies to enter the rapidly expanding Russian market.
On the other hand, Russian scientific companies want to get contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of famous Soviet research institutes and societies.
It houses the Moscow Institute of Electrotechnical Engineering, the major firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The commune was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for weapons research.
Zelenograd (literally translated “Green City”) takes its name from the wooded hills in which the research centres are located.
The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be set high enough.
For its supporters it is nothing less than “the new heart of Europe”.
S21 is much more than the burying of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg into a desperate chaos of construction sites for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 80s.
Headline stations, with tracks ending in the city, had a reputation at the time as the relics of 19th-century transport technology that acted as the brake shoe of modern rail traffic because it used to take a long time to move locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that’s what needs to be done.
That is why the main railway stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And also in Stuttgart: a train station, which is located about halfway on the Trans-European Railway between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
The realization of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality for a long time.
Even the most ambitious planners acknowledged that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
In fact, head-of-line stations are no longer really a problem of entry and exit since there are modern trains, reversible with railcars and pilot cars at both ends.
However, we are now launching the construction of Stuttgart 21 next to the new route of the inter-city line to Ulm.
Regional and local policies have won.
The railway company is the party because it is the taxpayer who bears the risk of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic and not the public enterprise.
From an urban point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
We get an urban space that – if we believe the graphs of the computer-generated planners – will be very green.
For the rail transport system, the S21 is detrimental.
The passing station and the enlargement of the section are designed for a traffic of people to which was attributed - and this is typical of the 1980s - a huge growth.
At the time, there was no competition for cheap flights.
Modern traffic policy should first focus on strengthening freight traffic because rail transport is much more environmentally friendly than trucking on the road.
But the new route, with its inclinations, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious, indirectly concerns many other railway projects.
For example, six billion euros will be swallowed up in the Swabian project.
That's the official number.
Experts believe that ten to fifteen billion is more realistic.
One thing is for sure, in the next decade this money will be missing for other points of connection and congestion in the network.
The Ministry of Transport lists a total of 60 major projects.
One of the most important is the enlargement of the section through the Rhine Valley by 180 good kilometers.
Since 1987 this line has been built in slow motion.
It would be really urgent to press the mushroom thoroughly here.
But the S21 project has the effect of a brake shoe.
The Rhine Valley route is on its way to becoming the bottleneck for international goods traffic, right in the heart of Europe.
