This is why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a particular talent.
There is only one step between dreaming and hallucinating.
In our world that is too focused on consciousness, we unfortunately quickly tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the clinic of psychiatry and psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease that also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the form of experience called oniroid, a particular form of the modification of consciousness awakened by the dream.
The dream-like experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot distinguish from the dream even when he is awake.
The oniroid state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies such as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully aware, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that damages his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dreaming and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation that is itself intolerable, a capacity for organization that is given to us men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurich-based art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Changing the Heart" as a soul-saving action.
He is 49 years old, at the time his conscious departs for a journey of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is condemned to remain immobile in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created from scratch, visiting foreign places, traveling back in time . He sees himself as an old man lying in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
