He is kidnapped by a Greek motorcyclist who takes him to his country, surfs with his hospital bed in the snowy Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He completely absorbs himself into this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes describing what he has experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental travel are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and more intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience bursts the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, dream delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even when awake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten "can cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
