75% of working mothers had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for younger generation women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fertility and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of employment occupied.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have a poorly stable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
In contrast, women in stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are repelling entry into life as a couple and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average 3.7 years after settling in as a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those who work in the public sector. "These data show that women with a stable job needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to delay the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised greatly influences maternity, but less the date of beginning of common life, "explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child late.
The difference also remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35- to 49-year-old group, those who completed elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average.
"Another disctinction also appears among women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle-level or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child, "says Delgado.
